## JavaScript Debounce Function

A debounce function limits how often a function can fire by delaying its execution until a specified wait time has passed since the last call.

```javascript
// Debounce function
function debounce(fn, delay) {
  let timer;
  return function (...args) {
    clearTimeout(timer);
    timer = setTimeout(() => fn.apply(this, args), delay);
  };
}

// --- Example Usage ---

// Simulates a search input that only fires after the user stops typing for 300ms
const handleSearch = debounce((query) => {
  console.log(`Searching for: "${query}"`);
}, 300);

// Simulating rapid keystrokes
handleSearch("r");        // cancelled
handleSearch("re");       // cancelled
handleSearch("rea");      // cancelled
handleSearch("reac");     // cancelled
handleSearch("react");    // ✅ fires after 300ms — logs: Searching for: "react"
```

### How it works

| Step | What happens |
|------|-------------|
| 1 | A call comes in and starts a timer |
| 2 | If another call arrives before the timer ends, it **resets** the timer |
| 3 | Only the **last** call — once the wait has elapsed — actually executes |

### Common use cases
- **Search inputs** — avoid an API call on every keystroke
- **Window resize** — recalculate layout only after resizing stops
- **Button clicks** — prevent accidental double submissions
